sentence-detokenized: The EU rejects Germany's call to boycott British lamb.
Peter Blackburn
BRUSSELS 1996-08-22
The European Commission said on Thursday it disagreed with Germany's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb until scientists determine whether mad cow disease can be transmitted to sheep.

Germany's representative on the European Union's veterinary committee, Werner Zwingmann, said on Wednesday that consumers should buy sheep meat from countries other than Britain until scientific advice is clearer.
"We do not support such a recommendation because we do not see the reasons for it," said the Commission's chief spokesman Nikolaus van der Pas at a press briefing.
He said that further scientific study was needed and that if action was needed, it should be taken by the European Union.

He said the proposal made last month by EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler to ban sheep brain, spleen and spinal cord from the food and feed chains was a very specific precautionary measure to protect human health.
Fischler proposed EU-wide measures after Britain and France reported that, under laboratory conditions, sheep could contract bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) - mad cow disease.

But Fischler agreed to review his proposal after the EU's Standing Veterinary Committee, made up of national animal health officials, questioned whether such action was justified as the risk to human health was minimal.
At a meeting of EU agriculture ministers, Spanish Agriculture Minister Loyola de Palacio accused Fischler of causing unjustified concern by "dangerous generalisation".
Only France and Great Britain supported Fischler's proposal.
The EU's veterinary and multidisciplinary scientific committees are due to review the issue early next month and make recommendations to senior veterinary officials.
Sheep have long been known to contract scrapie, a brain disease similar to BSE, which is believed to have been transmitted to cattle through feed containing animal waste.

British farmers denied on Thursday that their sheep posed any danger to human health, but expressed concern that the German government's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb could influence European consumers.
"What we have to be extremely careful about is how other countries will follow Germany's lead," John Lloyd Jones, president of the Welsh National Farmers' Union (NFU), told BBC radio.

Bonn led efforts to protect public health after consumer confidence collapsed in March following a British report suggesting that humans could contract a disease similar to mad cow disease by eating contaminated beef.
Germany imported 47,600 sheep from Britain last year, almost half of total imports.
It imported 4,275 tonnes of British mutton, around 10% of total imports.
A rare Hendrix song draft sells for nearly $17,000.
A rare handwritten draft of a song by American guitar legend Jimi Hendrix sold for nearly $17,000 on Thursday at an auction of some of the late musician's favourite possessions.
A Florida restaurant paid £10,925 ($16,935) for the draft of "Ain't No Telling", which Hendrix wrote on a London hotel stationery in late 1966.
At the end of a January 1967 concert in the English city of Nottingham, he threw the sheet of paper into the audience, where it was retrieved by a fan.
Buyers also snapped up 16 other items auctioned by Hendrix's former girlfriend, Kathy Etchingham, who lived with him from 1966 to 1969.
Among them is a black lacquer and mother-of-pearl inlaid box used by Hendrix to store his drugs, which an anonymous Australian buyer purchased for £5,060 ($7,845).
The guitarist died of a drug overdose in 1970 at the age of 27.
China believes that Taiwan is spoiling the atmosphere of the negotiations.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China on Thursday accused Taipei of spoiling the atmosphere for a resumption of cross-Strait talks with a visit to Ukraine by Taiwanese Vice President Lien Chan this week, which infuriated Beijing.

Speaking just hours after Chinese state media said it was time for political talks with Taiwan, Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang told Reuters: "The atmosphere necessary for the opening of the talks was disrupted by the Taiwanese authorities."
State media quoted China's top negotiator with Taipei, Tang Shubei, as telling a group of Taiwanese visitors on Wednesday that it was time for the rivals to hold political talks.
"The time has come for both sides to engage in political talks...
that is, to end the state of hostility," Tang was quoted as saying in Thursday's foreign edition of People's Daily.

Mr Shen of the foreign ministry told Reuters Television in an interview that he had read reports of Mr Tang's comments, but did not elaborate on why the negotiator felt the time was right to talk to Taiwan, which Beijing considers a renegade province.
China, which has long opposed all Taipei's efforts to gain greater international recognition, was infuriated by this week's visit to Ukraine by Taiwanese Vice President Lien.
China believes that the time is right for negotiations on Taiwan.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China said that it was time for political talks with Taiwan and that the rival island should take concrete steps to achieve this goal.

Consultations are expected to be held to set the timing and format of the talks, the official Xinhua news agency said late Wednesday, citing Tang Shubei, executive vice president of the Association for Relations across the Taiwan Strait.
German car registrations in July were 14.2% higher than a year earlier.
FRANKFURT 1996-08-22
First-time registrations of motor vehicles in Germany jumped by 14.2 percent in July this year compared to the previous year, the Federal Motor Vehicle Office said on Thursday.
The agency reported that 356,725 new cars were registered in July 1996 - 304,850 passenger cars and 15,613 trucks.
These figures represent an increase of 13.6% for passenger cars and a decrease of 2.2% for trucks compared to July 1995.
Motorbike registrations increased by 32.7% during this period.
The growth was partly due to an increase in the number of Germans buying German cars abroad, while manufacturers said domestic demand was weak, the federal office said.
Almost all German car manufacturers recorded an increase in registrations during this period.
Volkswagen AG achieved 77,719 registrations, just over a quarter of the total.
Opel AG and General Motors came second with 49,269 registrations, or 16.4 percent of the total.
Third place went to Ford with 35,563 registrations, or 11.7%.
Only Seat and Porsche recorded a decrease in registrations in July 1996 compared to July of the previous year.
Seat recorded 3,420 registrations, compared to 5,522 registrations in July of the previous year.
Porsche registrations fell from 643 to 554.

Israel plays down fears of war with Syria.
Colleen Siegel
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel's outgoing peace negotiator with Syria said on Thursday that the current tensions between the two countries seemed like a storm in a teacup.
Itamar Rabinovich, who as Israel's ambassador to Washington conducted unsuccessful negotiations with Syria, told Israeli radio that it appeared Damascus wanted to talk rather than fight.
"It seems to me that the {(1) [MISC] Syrian priority} is always to negotiate.
The Syrians are confused, they are certainly tense, but the general assessment here in Washington is that this is basically a storm in a teapot," he said.
Mr Rabinovich is completing his term as ambassador.
He will be replaced by Eliahu Ben-Elissar, a former Israeli envoy to Egypt and a right-wing Likud Party politician.
On Wednesday, Israel sent a message to Syria, via Washington, that it was committed to peace and wanted to open negotiations without preconditions.
But she blamed Damascus for creating what she called a dangerous atmosphere.
On Wednesday, Syria accused Israel of launching a hysterical campaign against it after Israeli television reported that Damascus had recently test-fired a missile.
It stated that its arms purchases were for defensive purposes.

"The message we sent to (Syrian President Hafez al-) Assad is that Israel is ready at any time, without preconditions, to start peace negotiations," Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said in an interview on Israeli radio.
Tensions have risen since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June and pledged to retain the Golan Heights, which Israel conquered from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been stalled over the Golan since 1991, despite the willingness of the previous government to make concessions on the Golan.
The last peace talks between the two sides took place in February.
"The voices coming out of Damascus are bad, not good.
The media...
are full of expressions and statements that must be worrying...
This artificial atmosphere is very dangerous because those who propagate it could become its prisoners," said Mr Levy.
"We expect Syria, if its face is turned towards peace, to respond to Israel's message to start peace negotiations, because that is our goal," he said. "
We don't want war, God forbid.
Wars do not benefit anyone. "
Israel's Channel Two television said Damascus had sent an "appeasement signal" to Israel.
It did not give a source for this report.
Spokespersons for Netanyahu and Levy said they could not confirm this.
The television also said that Netanyahu had sent messages to reassure Syria via Cairo, the United States and Moscow.
Polish diplomat denies nurses trapped in Libya.
A Polish diplomat on Thursday denied a report in a Polish tabloid this week that Libya was denying exit visas to 100 Polish nurses trying to return home after working in the North African country.
"This is not true.

To date, we are not aware of any nurse being stranded or detained in Libya without her will, and we have not received any complaints," Tadeusz Awdankiewicz, charge d'affaires at the Polish embassy in Tripoli, told Reuters by phone.

The Polish labour ministry said this week that it would send a team to Libya to investigate, but Awdankiewicz said the investigation was triggered by some nurses who complained about their working conditions, including the non-payment of their salaries.
He said that there are an estimated 800 Polish nurses working in Libya.
Two Iranian opposition leaders meet in Baghdad.
Hassan Hafidh
BAGHDAD 1996-08-22
A group of Iranian exiles based in Iraq pledged on Thursday to support Iranian Kurdish rebels after they were attacked by Iranian troops in the heart of Iraq last month.

A Mojahedin Khalq statement said that its leader Massoud Rajavi met on Wednesday in Baghdad with the Secretary General of the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI) Hassan Rastegar and expressed his support for the rebel Kurds in Iran.
"Rajavi stressed that the Iranian Resistance would continue to stand by his fellow Kurds and the resistance movement in Iranian Kurdistan.
A spokesman for the group said the meeting "signals a new level of cooperation between Mujahideen Khalq and the Iranian Kurdish opposition".
Iran heavily bombed targets in northern Iraq in July in pursuit of KDPI guerrillas based in Iraqi Kurdish areas outside the control of the Baghdad government.
The Iraqi Kurdish areas bordering Iran are under the control of the guerrillas of the Iraqi Kurdish group Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK).
The PUK and the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iraq (KDP), the two main Iraqi Kurdish factions, have controlled northern Iraq since Iraqi forces were driven out of Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
Clashes between the two sides broke out last weekend. It was the most serious fighting since a US-sponsored ceasefire last year.
Mujahideen Khalq said Iranian troops had also shelled KDP positions in the Qasri area of Suleimaniya province near the Iranian border over the past two days.
He said that around 100 Iraqi Kurds had been killed or injured in the attack.
Both Iran and Turkey are conducting air and ground strikes on targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of their own Kurdish rebels.
A US-led air force in southern Turkey is protecting Iraqi Kurds from possible attacks by Baghdad troops.
The Saudi riyal remains stable in a quiet summer market.
The Saudi riyal spot rate against the dollar and riyal interbank deposit rates have remained stable this week amid a calm summer, according to currency traders in the kingdom.
"There has been no change in Saudi riyal rates.
The market was very quiet because of the summer holidays," said one trader.
The spot riyal was placed at 3.7504 / 06 to the dollar.
One-month interbank deposits were at 5-1/2, 3/8 per cent, three months at 5-5/8, 1/2 per cent and six months at 5-3/4, 5/8 per cent.
The one-year funds were at six, 5-7/8 per cent.
Israel approves Arafat's flight to the West Bank.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel on Thursday allowed Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to fly over its territory into the West Bank, ending a brief crisis between Israel and the PLO, an adviser to Arafat said.
"The problem is solved.
The president's plane has been given permission to pass through Israeli airspace, but the president is not expected to visit the West Bank until Monday, Nabil Abu Rdainah told Reuters.

Arafat was due to meet former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres in the West Bank city of Ramallah, but the venue was moved to Gaza after Israel denied the Palestinian leader's helicopters permission to fly.
Palestinian officials accused right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of trying to prevent the Ramallah meeting by keeping Arafat down.
Arafat then cancelled a meeting between Israeli and PLO officials on civil affairs at the Allenby Bridge crossing between Jordan and the West Bank.
Abu Rdainah said Arafat decided not to fly to the West Bank on Thursday, after Israel lifted the ban, because he had a busy schedule in Gaza and would not be free until Monday.
Arafat to meet Peres in Gaza after flight ban.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22

Yasser Arafat will meet Shimon Peres in Gaza on Thursday, after Palestinians said Israel's right-wing government had prevented the Palestinian leader from travelling to the West Bank for talks with the former prime minister.
